      body: "### Version\r\n2.7.2\r\n\r\n### Reproduction link\r\n[codepen.io](https://codepen.io/Michael9411/pen/Yzayvdx)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\nClick button 'Exchange'.\r\n\r\n### What is expected?\r\nThe callback should not gets called, since new value is same as old value.\r\n\r\n### What is actually happening?\r\nThe callback gets called, but new value is same as old value. \r\n\r\n---\r\nYou may have noticed that a computed function watched with 'deep' option. This wired scenario came out when I studied a piece of Vue source code. \r\nhttps://github.com/vuejs/vue/blob/018d29af5fa171b2d2f4793c5d471f21bb7cd1e7/src/core/observer/watcher.ts#L205-L212\r\nAs you can see, the new value is same as the old (both are primitive values), but the callback gets called. So, is it better below?  \r\n```\r\n if ( \r\n   value !== this.value || \r\n   // Deep watchers and watchers on Object/Arrays should fire even \r\n   // when the value is the same, because the value may \r\n   // have mutated. \r\n   isObject(value) &&\r\n   this.deep \r\n ) {\r\n```\r\n\r\n<!-- generated by vue-issues. DO NOT REMOVE -->",
